  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Following the Rhyme of a Traveler's View at Gyeongseong
  author: Kwon Jin
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Stone fortifications stretch across the void, half-suspended in air.
    A lonely village nestles before the sea.
    Once a theater of ancient battles,
    Now I witness the smoke of great peace.

    Past events drift beyond the floating clouds,
    While flowing years settle upon my temple's edge.
    How many leagues from Chang'an is this place?
    Gazing into the distance, my heart dissolves into vastness.
  footnotes:
    - Chang'an, the ancient Chinese capital, symbolizes the center of civilization and authority—here used metaphorically to question one's distance from power and stability.
    - The imagery of 'floating clouds' and 'flowing years' reflects traditional Buddhist and Daoist themes of impermanence prevalent in East Asian poetry.
